SIMPLE: relax
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Relax
<hw>Re*lax"</hw> <pr>(r?-l?ks")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Relaxed</conjf>
<pr>(-l?kst")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Relaxing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>relaxare</ets>; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>laxare</ets> to loose, to slacken, from
<ets>laxus</ets> loose. See <er>Lax</er>, and cf. <er>Relay</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <er>Release</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make lax or
loose; to make less close, firm, rigid, tense, or the like; to slacken;
to loosen; to open; <as>as, to <ex>relax</ex> a rope or cord; to
<ex>relax</ex> the muscles or sinews.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Horror . . . all his joints <qex>relaxed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor served it to <qex>relax</qex> their serried files.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make less severe or rigorous; to abate the
stringency of; to remit in respect to strenuousness, earnestness, or
effort; <as>as, to <ex>relax</ex> discipline; to <ex>relax</ex> one's
attention or endeavors.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The statute of mortmain was at several times <qex>relaxed</qex> by
the legislature.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, to relieve from attention or effort; to ease;
to recreate; to divert; <as>as, amusement <ex>relaxes</ex> the
mind</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To relieve from constipation; to loosen; to open;
<as>as, an aperient <ex>relaxes</ex> the bowels</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To slacken; loosen; loose; remit; abate;
mitigate; ease; unbend; divert.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relax</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Relax
<hw>Re*lax"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become lax, weak,
or loose; <as>as, to let one's grasp <ex>relax</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His knees <qex>relax</qex> with toil.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To abate in severity; to become less
rigorous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In others she <qex>relaxed</qex> again,⟦br⟧
And governed with a looser rein.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To remit attention or effort; to become less
diligent; to unbend; <as>as, to <ex>relax</ex> in study</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relax</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Relax
<hw>Re*lax"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Relaxation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Feltham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relax</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Relax
<hw>Re**lax"</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Relaxed; lax; hence, remiss;
careless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relaxable</ent>⟦br⟧
